data.content:
Here's what breaks in each case and the fixes:

---

### 1. `GenericShift.cs` — Consistent shift behavior in generic math

In .NET 9, shift operations on small types (`byte`, `short`, etc.) via generic math were **inconsistent**. In .NET 10, shift behavior is now **consistent** across all types. `ShiftLeft<byte>(0xFF, 8)` will still return `0` (byte has only 8 bits), but other small types that previously gave inconsistent results will now behave uniformly. **If your code relied on the old inconsistent behavior, update your logic expectations.** No code change needed unless you depended on the quirks.

---

### 2. `ApiClient.cs` — Streaming HTTP responses enabled by default in Blazor WASM

In .NET 10, **streaming HTTP responses are enabled by default in browser-based HTTP clients** (Blazor WebAssembly). The synchronous `stream.Read()` call may now receive partial data incrementally instead of a fully-buffered response. The fix is to use async reads and loop until completion:

```csharp
var response = await httpClient.GetAsync(url);
var stream = await response.Content.ReadAsStreamAsync();
var buffer = new byte[4096];
int bytesRead;
while ((bytesRead = await stream.ReadAsync(buffer, 0, buffer.Length)) > 0)
{
    // process bytesRead bytes from buffer
}
```

---

### 3. `Archiver.cs` — PaxTarEntry no longer includes atime/ctime by default

In .NET 10, `GnuTarEntry`/`PaxTarEntry` **no longer include `AccessTime` and `ChangeTime` by default**. Your assumption that they'd be set to "now" is no longer valid. **Fix: set them explicitly:**

```csharp
var entry = new PaxTarEntry(TarEntryType.RegularFile, "data.txt");
entry.AccessTime = DateTimeOffset.UtcNow;
entry.ChangeTime = DateTimeOffset.UtcNow;
archive.WriteEntry(entry);
```

---

### 4. `App.csproj` + HTTP/3 — HTTP/3 stripped by trimmer

When `<PublishTrimmed>true</PublishTrimmed>` is set, **HTTP/3 implementation code is completely removed by the trimmer** in .NET 10. Your HTTP/3 connections to the backend will silently fail or fall back. **Fix: add `<Http3Support>true</Http3Support>`:**

```xml
<PropertyGroup>
  <PublishTrimmed>true</PublishTrimmed>
  <Http3Support>true</Http3Support>
</PropertyGroup>
```

This preserves the HTTP/3 code paths during trimming.
